# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: fair-division-algorithms
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:fair-division-algorithms/adjusted-winner-procedure] Involves splitting at most one good between the parties.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/adjusted-winner-procedure] It is the only procedure that can satisfy all four properties simultaneously.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/adjusted-winner-procedure] Despite this, however, there are no accounts of the algorithm actually being used to resolve disputes.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/adjusted-winner-procedure] The procedure was designed by Steven Brams and Alan D.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/adjusted-winner-procedure] Taylor, and published in their book on fair division and later in a stand-alone book.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/adjusted-winner-procedure] Adjusted Winning was previously patented in the United States, but expired in 2016.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/adjusted-winner-procedure] Each party is given the list of goods and an equal, fixed number of points to distribute among them.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/adjusted-winner-procedure] They then assign values to each good and submit their (sealed) list of bids to an arbiter, who assigns each item to its highest bidder.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/adjusted-winner-procedure] The next good is then divided between the parties such that their values become the same.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/adjusted-winner-procedure] The goods would first be divided such that Alice receives good 1, while Bob receives goods 2, 3, and 4.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/adjusted-winner-procedure] Moving Good 2 from Bob to Alice would cause Alice to have a valuation greater than Bob's (161 versus 100), so no goods are transferred.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/adjusted-winner-procedure] Instead, Good 2 is split between Alice and Bob: Alice receives ${\frac {95}{156}}$ th of the good (approximately 60.9%), while Bob receives ${\frac {61}{156}}$ th (approximately 39.1%).
[src:fair-division-algorithms/adjusted-winner-procedure] There are no cases of Adjusted Winner being used to resolve real-life disputes.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/adjusted-winner-procedure] AW is not a truthful mechanism: a party can gain from spying on its opponent and modifying their reports in order to get a larger share.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/adjusted-winner-procedure] However, Adjusted Winner always has an approximate Nash equilibrium, and under informed tie-breaking, also a pure Nash equilibrium.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/adjusted-winner-procedure] As patented, the algorithm assumes the parties have additive utility functions: the value of their goods is equal to the sum of the individual goods' values.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/adjusted-winner-procedure] It does not handle, for example, multiple instances of a good with diminishing marginal utilities.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/adjusted-winner-procedure] The algorithm also is designed for two parties only; when there are three or more parties, there may be no allocation that is simultaneously envy-free, equitable, and Pareto-optimal.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/adjusted-winner-procedure] The only Pareto-optimal and equitable allocation would be the one giving good 1 to Alice, good 2 to Bob, and good 3 to Carl; however, this allocation would not be envy-free since Alice would envy Bob.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/adjusted-winner-procedure] Moreover, it is possible to find an allocation that, while being Pareto-optimal/envy-free or Pareto-optimal/equitable, would minimize the number of objects that have to be shared between two or more parties.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/adjusted-winner-procedure] This it usually considered the generalization of the Adjusted Winner procedure to three or more parties.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/adjusted-winner-procedure] Adjusted Winner is designed for agents with positive valuations over the items.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/adjusted-winner-procedure] It can be generalized for parties with mixed (positive and negative) valuations, however.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/adjusted-winner-procedure] The Brams–Taylor procedure was designed by the same authors, but it is instead a procedure for envy-free cake-cutting: it handles heterogeneous resources ("cake") which are more challenging to divide than Adjusted Winning's homogeneous goods.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/adjusted-winner-procedure] Accordingly, BT guarantees only envy-freeness, not any other attributes.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/adjusted-winner-procedure] The article on Fair division experiments describes some laboratory experiments comparing AW to related procedures.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] An **envy-free cake-cutting** is a kind of fair cake-cutting.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] It is a division of a heterogeneous resource ("cake") that satisfies the envy-free criterion, namely, that every partner feels that their allocated share is at least as good as any other share, according to their own subjective valuation.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] What is the runtime complexity of envy-free cake-cutting?
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] When there are only two partners, the problem is easy and was solved in antiquity by the divide and choose protocol.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] When there are three or more partners, the problem becomes much more challenging.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] Modern research into the fair cake-cutting problem started in the 1940s.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] The first fairness criterion studied was proportional division, and a procedure for *n* partners was soon found.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] The stronger criterion of envy-freeness was introduced into the cake-cutting problem by George Gamow and Marvin Stern in 1950s.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] A procedure for three partners and general pieces was found in 1960.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] A procedure for three partners and connected pieces was found only in 1980.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] Envy-free division for four or more partners had been an open problem until the 1990s, when three procedures for general pieces and a procedure for connected pieces were published.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] All these procedures are *unbounded* - they may require a number of steps which is not bounded in advance.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] The procedure for connected pieces may even require an *infinite* number of steps.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] Two lower bounds on the run-time complexity of envy-freeness were published in the 2000s.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] In the 2010s, several approximation procedures and procedures for special cases were published.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] The question whether bounded-time procedures exist for the case of general pieces had remained open for a long time.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] Haris Aziz and Simon Mackenzie presented a discrete envy-free protocol that requires at most $n^{n^{n^{n^{n^{n}}}}}$ or $n\uparrow \uparrow 6$ queries.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] There is still a very large gap between the lower bound and the procedure.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] As of October 2024, the exact run-time complexity of envy-freeness is still unknown.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] For the case of connected pieces, it was noted that the hardness result assumes that the entire cake must be divided.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] Note that it is *not* required that the preferences of the agents are represented by an additive function.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] The main concept in the proof is the *simplex of partitions*.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] Each partition with connected pieces can be uniquely represented by *n*−1 numbers in [0,1] which represent the cut locations.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] The union of all partitions is a simplex.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] For each partition, each agent has one or more pieces which they weakly prefer.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] For every agent, the partition simplex is covered by *n* parts, possibly overlapping at their boundaries, such that for all partitions in part *i*, the agent prefers piece *i*.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] In the interior of part *i*, the agent prefers *only* piece *i*, while in the boundary of part *i*, the agent also prefers some other pieces.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] So for every *i*, there is a certain region in the partition simplex in which at least one agent prefers only piece *i*.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] Using a certain topological lemma (that is similar to the Knaster–Kuratowski–Mazurkiewicz lemma), it is possible to prove that the intersection of all *U**i*'s is non-empty.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] Hence, there is a partition in which every piece is the unique preference of an agent.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] Since the number of pieces equals the number of agents, we can allocate each piece to the agent that prefers it and get an envy-free allocation.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] These are continuous procedures - they rely on people moving knives continuously and simultaneously.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] They cannot be executed in a finite number of discrete steps.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] For *n* agents, an envy-free division can be found by Simmons' cake-cutting protocol.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] The protocol uses a *simplex of partitions* similar to the one used in Stromquist's existence proof.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] It generates a sequence of partitions which converges to an envy-free partition.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] The convergence might take infinitely many steps.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] It is not a coincidence that all these algorithms may require infinitely many queries.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] As we show in the following subsection, it may be impossible to find an envy-free cake-cutting with connected pieces with a finite number of queries.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] An envy-free division with connected pieces for 3 or more agents cannot be found by a finite protocol in the Robertson–Webb query model.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] The reason this result doesn't contradict the previously mentioned algorithms is that they are not finite in the mathematical sense.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] The impossibility proof uses a *rigid measure system* (RMS) – a system of *n* value measures, for which an envy-free division must cut the cake at very specific locations.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] Then, finding an envy-free division reduces to finding these specific locations.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] Assuming the cake is the real interval [0,1], finding an envy-free division using queries to the agents is equivalent to finding a real number in the interval [0,1] using yes/no questions.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] This might require an infinite number of questions.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] A RMS for three agents can be constructed as follows.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] This implies that, if all queries answered so far were outside the *ε*-neighbourhood of *x* and *y*, then agent *i* has no way to know whether we are in the old RMS or in the new RMS.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] As long as the protocol makes cuts at points other than *x* and *y*, let it continue.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] Whenever the protocol asks agent *i* to make a cut at *x* or *y*, switch to a different RMS with *x'≠x* and *y'≠y*, making sure that the values are the same for all previously made cuts.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] Thus the protocol can never make cuts at the correct *x* and *y* required for an envy-free division.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] Since envy-free cake-cutting with connected pieces cannot be done in finite time, cake-cutters have tried to find work-arounds.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] One work-around is looking for divisions which are only *approximately-envy-free*.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] There are two ways to define the approximation - in units of *length* or in units of *value*.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] The parameter *δ* represents the tolerance of the partners in units of length.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] E.g., if land is divided and the partners agree that a difference of 0.01 meter in the location of the border is not relevant to them, then it makes sense to look for a 0.01-multi-partition which is envy-free.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] Deng at al present a modification of Simmons' cake-cutting protocol which finds an envy-free *δ*-multi-partition using $O[(1/\delta )^{n-2}]$ queries.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] Even when the utility functions are given explicitly by polynomial-time algorithms, the envy-free cake-cutting problem is PPAD-complete.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] If all value measures are Lipschitz continuous, then the two approximation definitions are related.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] Then, every partition in an envy-free *δ*-multi-partition is *ε*-envy-free.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] Hence, Deng et al.'s results prove that, if all partners have Lipschitz continuous valuations, an *ε*-envy-free partition can be found with $\Theta [(1/\epsilon )^{n-2}]$ queries with general valuations.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] With additive valuations, for any ε > 0, an ε-envy-free connected cake-cutting requires at least Ω(log ε−1) queries.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] For 3 agents, an O(log ε−1) protocol exists.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] For 4 or more agents, the best known protocol requires O(*n* ε−1), which shows an exponential gap in the query complexity.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] Moreover, although the latter protocol has query complexity polynomial in *n*, its computational complexity is exponential in *n*, even for constant ε.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] If polynomial-time computation is required, the best-known approximation is $1/3$ -envy-freeness.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] Another restriction on the valuations is that they are *piecewise-constant* - for each agent, there are at most *m* desired intervals, and the agent's value-density in each interval is constant.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] Under this assumption, a connected envy-free allocation can be found by solving ${\frac {n\cdot (2mn+n-1)!}{(2mn)!}}\in O(m^{n})$ linear programs.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] Thus, when *n* is constant, the problem is polynomial in *m*.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] It is not known whether there exists a bounded-time envy-free and proportional division procedure for four or more partners with connected pieces.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] Most procedures for cake-cutting with connected pieces assume that the cake is a 1-dimensional interval and the pieces are 1-dimensional sub-intervals.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] Often, it is desirable that the pieces have a certain geometric shape, such as a square.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] With such constraints, it may be impossible to divide the entire cake (e.g., a square cannot be divided to two squares), so we must allow free disposal.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] As explained above, when free disposal is allowed, the procedures are measured by their level of *proportionality* - the value that they guarantee to all agents.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] An envy-free division exists even with non-additive value functions, multi-dimensional simplex cake, and the pieces must be polytopes.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] For three partners, the Selfridge–Conway discrete procedure makes an envy-free division with at most 5 cuts.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] For four partners, The Brams–Taylor–Zwicker procedure makes an envy-free division with at most 11 cuts.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] For five partners, a procedure by Saberi and Wang makes an envy-free division with a bounded number of cuts.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] Both these procedures use Austin's procedure for two partners and general fractions as an initial step.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] Hence, these procedures should be considered infinite - they cannot be completed using a finite number of steps.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] For four or more partners, there are three algorithms which are finite but unbounded - there is no fixed bound on the number of cuts required.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] Although the protocols are different, the main idea behind them is similar: Divide the cake to a finite but unbounded number of "crumbs", each of which is so small that its value for all partners is negligible.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] Then combine the crumbs in a sophisticated way to get the desired division.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] William Gasarch has compared the three unbounded algorithms using ordinal numbers.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] The question of whether envy-free cake-cutting can be done in bounded time for four or more partners had been open for many years.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] It was finally solved in 2016 by Haris Aziz and Simon Mackenzie.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] Initially they developed a bounded-time algorithm for four partners.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] Then they extended their algorithm to handle any number of partners.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] Their algorithm requires at most $n^{n^{n^{n^{n^{n}}}}}$ queries.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] While this number is bounded, it is very far from the lower bound of $\Omega (n^{2})$ .
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] So the question of how many queries are required for envy-free cake-cutting is still open.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] A reentrant variant of the last diminisher protocol finds an additive approximation to an envy-free division in bounded time.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] Specifically, for every constant $\epsilon >0$ , it returns a division in which the value of each partner is at least the largest value minus $\epsilon$ , in time $n^{2}/\epsilon$ .
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] If all value measures are *piecewise linear*, there is an algorithm which is polynomial in the size of the representation of the value functions.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] The number of queries is $O(n^{6}k\ln {k})$ , where k is the number of discontinuities in the derivatives of the value density functions.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] Every envy-free procedure for *n* people requires at least Ω(*n*2) queries in the Robertson–Webb query model.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] The proof relies on a careful analysis of the amount of information the algorithm has on each partner.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] Both proofs work only for additive and non-atomic value measures, and rely on the ability to give each partner a large number of disconnected pieces.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] A common generalization of the envy-free criterion is that each of the partners has a different entitlement.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] I.e., for every partner *i* there is a weight *wi* describing the fraction of the cake that they are entitled to receive (the sum of all *wi* is 1).
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] Then a weighted-envy-free division is defined as follows.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] I.e., every partner thinks that their allocation relative to their entitlement is at least as large as any other allocation relative to the other partner's entitlement.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] When all weights are the same (and equal to 1/*n*), this definition reduces to the standard definition of envy-freeness.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] When the pieces may be disconnected, a weighted envy-free division always exists and can be found by the Robertson-Webb protocol, for any set of weights.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] Zeng presented an alternative algorithm for approximate weighted envy-free division, which requires a smaller number of cuts.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] But when the pieces must be connected, a weighted envy-free division may not exist.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] It is known that weighted-proportional allocation with connected pieces may not exist: see proportional cake-cutting with different entitlements for an example.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] Note that there is an alternative definition of weighted-envy-free division, where the weights are assigned to *pieces* rather than to agents.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] In some cases, the 'cake' to be divided has a negative value.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] For example, it might be piece of lawn that has to be mowed, or a piece of wasteland that has to be cleaned.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] Then, the cake is a 'heterogeneous bad' rather than a 'heterogeneous good'.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] Some procedures for envy-free cake-cutting can be adapted to work for a bad cake, but the adaptation is often not trivial.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/envy-free-cake-cutting] See envy-free chore division for more details.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] There are many different kinds of fair division problems, depending on the nature of goods to divide, the criteria for fairness, the nature of the players and their preferences, and other criteria for evaluating the quality of the division.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] The archetypal fair division algorithm is divide and choose.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] The research in fair division can be seen as an extension of this procedure to various more complex settings.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] The problem arises in various real-world settings such as division of inheritance, partnership dissolutions, divorce settlements, electronic frequency allocation, airport traffic management, and exploitation of Earth observation satellites.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] It is an active research area in mathematics, economics (especially social choice theory), and dispute resolution.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] Formally, a fair division problem is defined by a set C (often called "the cake") and a group of n players.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] A division is a partition of C into n disjoint subsets: $C=X_{1}\sqcup X_{2}\sqcup \cdots \sqcup X_{n}$ , one subset per player.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] Most of what is normally called a fair division is not considered so by the theory because of the use of arbitration.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] This kind of situation happens quite often with mathematical theories named after real life problems.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] The decisions in the Talmud on entitlement when an estate is bankrupt reflect the development of complex ideas regarding fairness.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] However, they are the result of legal debates by rabbis rather than divisions according to the valuations of the claimants.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] According to the subjective theory of value, there cannot be an objective measure of the value of each item.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] Therefore, *objective fairness* is not possible, as different people may assign different values to each item.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] Empirical experiments on how people define the concept of fairness have given inconclusive results.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] Therefore, most current research on fairness focuses on concepts of *subjective fairness*.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] Each of the n people is assumed to have a personal, subjective *utility function* or *value function*, $V_{i}$ , which assigns a numerical value to each subset of C .
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] Often the functions are assumed to be normalized, so that every person values the empty set as 0 ( $V_{i}(\emptyset )=0$ for all i), and the entire set of items as 1 ( $V_{i}(C)=1$ for all i) if the items are desirable, and -1 if the items are undesirable.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] Based on these subjective value functions, there are a number of widely used criteria for a fair division.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] Some of these conflict with each other but often they can be combined.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] All the above criteria assume that the participants have equal entitlements.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] If different participants have different entitlements (e.g., in a partnership where each partner invested a different amount), then the fairness criteria should be adapted accordingly.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] See proportional cake-cutting with different entitlements.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] In addition to fairness, it is sometimes desired that the division be Pareto optimal, i.e., no other allocation would make someone better off without making someone else worse off.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] The term efficiency comes from the economics idea of the efficient market.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] A division where one player gets everything is optimal by this definition so on its own this does not guarantee even a fair share.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] See also efficient cake-cutting and the price of fairness.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] In the real world people sometimes have a very accurate idea of how the other players value the goods and they may care very much about it.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] The case where they have complete knowledge of each other's valuations can be modeled by game theory.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] Partial knowledge is very hard to model.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] A major part of the practical side of fair division is the devising and study of procedures that work well despite such partial knowledge or small mistakes.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] An additional requirement is that the fair division procedure be strategyproof, i.e. it should be a dominant strategy for the participants to report their true valuations.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] This requirement is usually very hard to satisfy, especially in combination with fairness and Pareto-efficiency.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] As a result, it is often weakened to incentive compatibility, which only requires players to report their true valuations if they behave according to a specified solution concept.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] It demonstrates that two agents with different tastes can divide a cake such that each of them believes that he got the best piece.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] A fair division procedure lists actions to be performed by the players in terms of the visible data and their valuations.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] A valid procedure is one that guarantees a fair division for every player who acts rationally according to their valuation.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] Where an action depends on a player's valuation the procedure is describing the strategy a rational player will follow.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] A player may act as if a piece had a different value but must be consistent.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] For instance if a procedure says the first player cuts the cake in two equal parts then the second player chooses a piece, then the first player cannot claim that the second player got more.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] It is assumed the aim of each player is to maximize the minimum amount they might get, or in other words, to achieve the maximin.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] Procedures can be divided into *discrete* vs.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] A discrete procedure would for instance only involve one person at a time cutting or marking a cake.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] Continuous procedures involve things like one player moving a knife and the other saying "stop".
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] Another type of continuous procedure involves a person assigning a value to every part of the cake.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] No finite protocol (even if unbounded) can guarantee an envy-free division of a cake among three or more players, if each player is to receive a single connected piece.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] However, this result applies only to the model presented in that work and not for cases where, for example, a mediator has full information of the players' valuation functions and proposes a division based on this information.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] Recently, the model of fair division has been extended from individual agents to *families* (pre-determined groups) of agents with fair division among groups.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] According to Sol Garfunkel, the cake-cutting problem had been one of the most important open problems in 20th century mathematics, when the most important variant of the problem was finally solved with the Brams-Taylor procedure by Steven Brams and Alan Taylor in 1995.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] Divide and choose's origins are undocumented.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] The related activities of bargaining and barter are also ancient.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] Negotiations involving more than two people are also quite common, the Potsdam Conference is a notable recent example.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] The theory of fair division dates back only to the end of the second world war.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] It was devised by a group of Polish mathematicians, Hugo Steinhaus, Bronisław Knaster and Stefan Banach, who used to meet in the Scottish Café in Lvov (then in Poland).
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] A proportional (fair division) division for any number of players called 'last-diminisher' was devised in 1944.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] This was attributed to Banach and Knaster by Steinhaus when he made the problem public for the first time at a meeting of the Econometric Society in Washington, D.C., on 17 September 1947.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-division] At that meeting he also proposed the problem of finding the smallest number of cuts necessary for such divisions.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] The indivisibility of the items implies that a fair division may not be possible.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] As an extreme example, if there is only a single item (e.g. a house), it must be given to a single partner, but this is not fair to the other partners.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] This is in contrast to the fair cake-cutting problem, where the dividend is divisible and a fair division always exists.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] In some cases, the indivisibility problem can be mitigated by introducing *monetary payments* or *time-based rotation*, or by discarding some of the items.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] But such solutions are not always available.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] The group should decide on a *fairness criterion*.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] Based on the preferences and the fairness criterion, a *fair assignment algorithm* should be executed to calculate a fair division.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] A naive way to determine the preferences is asking each partner to supply a numeric value for each possible bundle.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] For example, if the items to divide are a car and a bicycle, a partner may value the car as 800, the bicycle as 200, and the bundle {car, bicycle} as 900 (see Utility functions on indivisible goods for more examples).
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] The number of possible bundles can be huge: if there are m items then there are $2^{m}$ possible bundles.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] For example, if there are 16 items then each partner will have to present their preferences using 65536 numbers.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] The first problem motivates the use of ordinal utility rather than cardinal utility.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] In the ordinal model, each partner should only express a ranking over the $2^{m}$ different bundles, i.e., say which bundle is the best, which is the second-best, and so on.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] This may be easier than calculating exact numbers, but it is still difficult if the number of items is large.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] Under suitable assumptions, it is possible to *lift* the preferences on items to preferences on bundles.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] Then, the agents report their valuations/rankings on individual items, and the algorithm calculates for them their valuations/rankings on bundles.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] To make the item-assignment problem simpler, it is common to assume that all items are independent goods (so they are not substitute goods nor complementary goods).
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] The additivity implies that each partner can always choose a "preferable item" from the set of items on the table, and this choice is independent of the other items that the partner may have.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] This property is used by some fair assignment algorithms that will be described next.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] An *individual guarantee criterion* is a criterion that should hold for each individual partner, as long as the partner truthfully reports his preferences.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] The maximin-share (also called: max-min-fair-share guarantee) of an agent is the most preferred bundle he could guarantee himself as divider in divide and choose against adversarial opponents.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] An allocation is called *MMS-fair* if every agent receives a bundle that he weakly prefers over his MMS.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] The proportional-fair-share of an agent is 1/*n* of his utility from the entire set of items.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] An allocation is called *proportional* if every agent receives a bundle worth at least his proportional-fair-share.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] The min-max-fair-share of an agent is the minimal utility that she can hope to get from an allocation if all the other agents have the same preferences as her, when she always receives the best share.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] It is also the minimal utility that an agent can get for sure in the allocation game “Someone cuts, I choose first”.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] An allocation is *mFS-fair* if all agents receive a bundle that they weakly prefer over their mFS. mFS-fairness can be described as the result of the following negotiation process.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] Each agent can object to it by demanding that a different allocation be made by another agent, letting him choose first.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] Hence, an agent would object to an allocation only if in *all* partitions, there is a bundle that he strongly prefers over his current bundle.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] An allocation is mFS-fair iff no agent objects to it, i.e., for every agent there exists a partition in which all bundles are weakly worse than his current share.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] For every agent with subadditive utility, the mFS is worth *at least* $1/n$ .
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] Hence, every mFS-fair allocation is proportional.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] For every agent with superadditive utility, the MMSis worth *at most* $1/n$ .
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] Hence, every proportional allocation is MMS-fair.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] Both inclusions are strict, even when every agent has additive utility.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] The above implications do not hold when the agents' valuations are not sub/superadditive.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] Every agent weakly prefers his own bundle to any other bundle.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] Every envy-free allocation of all items is mFS-fair; this follows directly from the ordinal definitions and does not depend on additivity.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] If the valuations are additive, then an EF allocation is also proportional and MMS-fair.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] Otherwise, an EF allocation may be not proportional and even not MMS.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] This criterion is based on the following argument: the allocation process should be considered as a search for an equilibrium between the supply (the set of objects, each one having a public price) and the demand (the agents’ desires, each agent having the same budget for buying the objects).
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] A competitive equilibrium is reached when the supply matches the demand.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] The fairness argument is straightforward: prices and budgets are the same for everyone.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] CEEI implies EF regardless of additivity.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] When the agents' preferences are additive and strict (each bundle has a different value), CEEI implies Pareto efficiency.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] An advantage of global optimization criteria over individual criteria is that welfare-maximizing allocations are Pareto efficient.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] Traditional papers on fair allocation either assume that all items are divisible, or that all items are indivisible.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] Some recent papers study settings in which the distinction between divisible and indivisible is more fuzzy.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] Several works assume that all objects can be divided if needed (e.g. by shared ownership or time-sharing), but sharing is costly or undesirable.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] Therefore, it is desired to find a fair allocation with the smallest possible number of shared objects, or of sharings.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] Are there efficient algorithms for maximizing Utilitarian social welfare among EFM allocations?
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] Are there bounded or even finite algorithms for computing EFM allocations in the Robertson–Webb query model?
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] Does there always exist an EFM allocation when there are indivisible chores and a cake?
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] More generally: does there always exist an EFM allocation when both divisible items and indivisible items may be positive for some agents and negative for others?
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] Is there a truthful EFM algorithm for agents with binary additive valuations?
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] In this variant, different agents are entitled to different fractions of the resource.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] A common use-case is dividing cabinet ministries among parties in the coalition.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] It is common to assume that each party should receive ministries according to the number of seats it has in the parliament.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] The various fairness notions have to be adapted accordingly.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] In this variant, bundles are given not to individual agents but to groups of agents.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] Common use-cases are: dividing inheritance among families, or dividing facilities among departments in a university.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] All agents in the same group consume the same bundle, though they may value it differently.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] The classic item allocation setting corresponds to the special case in which all groups are singletons.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] With groups, it may be impossible to guarantee *unanimous fairness* (fairness in the eyes of all agents in each group), so it is often relaxed to *democratic fairness* (fairness in the eyes of e.g. at least half the agents in each group).
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] In this variant, each item provides utility not only to a single agent but to all agents.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] Different agents may attribute different utilities to the same item.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] Item *i,j* essentially represents the decision to give item *j* to agent *i*.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] This idea can be formalized to show a general reduction from private-goods allocation to public-goods allocation that retains the maximum Nash welfare allocation, as well as a similar reduction that retains the leximin optimal allocation.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] Common solution concepts for public goods allocation are core stability (which implies both Pareto-efficiency and proportionality), maximum Nash welfare, leximin optimality and proportionality up to one item.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] In this variant, several agents have to accept decisions on several issues.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] A common use-case is a family that has to decide what activity to do each day (here each issue is a day).
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] Each agent assigns different utilities to the various options in each issue.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] The classic item allocation setting corresponds to the special case in which each issue corresponds to an item, each decision option corresponds to giving that item to a particular agent, and the agents' utilities are zero for all options in which the item is given to someone else.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] In this case, proportionality means that the utility of each agent is at least 1/*n* of his "dictatorship utility", i.e., the utility he could get by picking the best option in each issue.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] Proportionality might be unattainable, but PROP1 is attainable by Round-robin item allocation.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] Often, the same items are allocated repeatedly.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] If the number of repetitions is a multiple of the number of agents, then it is possible to find in polynomial time a sequence of allocations that is envy-free and complete, and to find in exponential time a sequence that is proportional and Pareto-optimal.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] But, an envy-free and Pareto-optimal sequence may not exist.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] With two agents, if the number of repetitions is even, it is always possible to find a sequence that is envy-free and Pareto-optimal.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] Assume that m items should be distributed between n agents.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] Formally, in the deterministic setting, a solution describes a feasible allocation of the items to the agents — a partition of the set of items into n subsets (one for each agent).
[src:fair-division-algorithms/fair-item-allocation] In the stochastic setting, a solution is a probability distribution over the set ${\mathcal {A}}$ .
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] A **proportional cake-cutting** is a kind of fair cake-cutting.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] It is a division of a heterogeneous resource ("cake") that satisfies the proportionality criterion, namely, that every partner feels that their allocated share is worth at least 1/*n* of the total.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] Each person i has a value function $V_{i}$ .
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] For two people, divide and choose is the classic solution.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] One person divides the resource into what they believe are equal halves, and the other person chooses the half they prefer.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] The non-atomicity assumption guarantees that the cutter can indeed cut the cake to two equal pieces; the additivity assumption guarantees that both partners value their pieces as at least 1/2.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] There are many ways to extend this procedure to more than 2 people.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] Each way has its own advantages and disadvantages.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] By induction, it is possible to prove that each partner following the rules is guaranteed to get a value of 1/*n*, regardless of what the other partners do.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] This is a discrete procedure that can be played in turns.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] In the worst case, $n\times (n-1)/2=O(n^{2})$ actions are needed: one action per player per turn.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] However, most of these actions can be done on paper; only *n* − 1 cuts of the cake are actually needed.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] Hence, it is possible for all the pieces to be contiguous under certain circumstances.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] The **moving-knife procedure** is a continuous-time version of Last Diminisher.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] The advantage of this protocol is that it can be executed online – as new partners enter the party, the existing division is adjusted to accommodate them, without needing to restart the entire division process.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] The disadvantage is that the each partner receives a large number of disconnected pieces rather than a single connected piece.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] Using a divide-and-conquer strategy, it is possible to achieve a proportional division in time O(*n* log *n*).
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] It is possible to prove by induction that every partner playing by the rules is guaranteed a piece with a value of at least 1/*n*, regardless of what the other partners do.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] Thanks to the divide-and-choose strategy, the number of iterations is only O(log *n*), in contrast to O(*n*) in the Last Diminisher procedure.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] In each iteration, each partner is required to make a single mark.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] Hence, the total number of marks required is O(*n* log *n*).
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] This algorithm has a randomized version which can be used to reduce the number of marks; see Even-Paz algorithm.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] A different approach to cake-cutting is to let every partner draw a certain number of pieces depending on the number of partners, *p*(*n*), and give each partner one of his selected pieces, such that the pieces do not overlap.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] As a simple example of a selection procedure, assume the cake is a 1-dimensional interval and that each partner wants to receive a single contiguous interval.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] The protocol orders the *n*^2 candidates by increasing order of their eastern (from west to east) and select the interval with the most western eastern end.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] This interval is called a *final piece*.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] The protocol gives the final piece to its owner and remove all candidates intersected by it.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] Step #2 is then repeated with the remaining intervals of the remaining *n* − 1 partners.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] The selection rule in step #2 guarantees that, at each iteration, at most one interval of every partner is removed.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] Hence, after each iteration the number of intervals per partners is still equal to the number of partners, and the process can proceed until every partner receives an interval.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] This protocol requires each partner to answer *n* queries so the query complexity is O(*n*2), similarly to Last Diminisher.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] It is possible to use randomization in order to reduce the number of queries.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] The idea is that each partner reports, not the entire collection of *n* candidates but only a constant number *d* of candidates, picked at random.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] The query complexity is O(*n*), which is obviously the best possible.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] In many cases, it will still be possible to give each partner a single candidate such that the candidates do not overlap.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] However, there are scenarios in which such an allocation will be impossible.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] Each partner picks 2*d* candidate pieces uniformly at random, with replacement.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] The candidates are grouped into *d* pairs, which the partner reports to the algorithm.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] These *n⋅d* pairs are called *quarterfinal brackets*.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] From each quarterfinal bracket, the algorithm selects a single piece – the piece that intersects the fewer number of other candidate pieces.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] These *n⋅d* pieces are called *semifinal pieces*.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] For each partner, the algorithm selects a single piece; they are called *final pieces*.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] The final pieces are selected such that each point of the cake is covered by at most 2 final pieces (see below).
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] Each part of the cake which belongs to only a single final piece, is given to the owner of that piece.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] Each part of the cake which belongs to two final pieces, is divided proportionally by any deterministic proportional division algorithm.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] The algorithm guarantees that, with probability O(1*a*2), each partner receives at least half of one of his candidate pieces, which implies (if the values are additive) a value of at least 1/2*an*.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] There are O(*n*) candidate pieces and O(*n*) additional divisions in step #5, each of which takes O(1) time.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] Hence the total run-time of the algorithm is O(*n*).
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] The main challenge in this scheme is selecting the final pieces in step #4.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] For details, see Edmonds–Pruhs protocol.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] The hardness results are stated in terms of the Robertson–Webb query model, i.e., they relate to procedures asking the agents two types of queries: "Evaluate" and "Mark".
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] Every deterministic proportional division procedure for *n*≥3 partners must use at least *n* queries, even if all valuations are identical.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] Moreover, every deterministic or randomized proportional division procedure assigning each person a contiguous piece must use Ω(*n* log *n*) actions.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] Moreover, every deterministic proportional division procedure must use Ω(*n* log *n*) queries, even if the procedure is allowed to assign to each partner a piece that is a union of intervals, and even if the procedure is allowed to only guarantee *approximate fairness*.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] The proof is based on lower bounding the complexity to find, for a single player, a piece of cake that is both rich in value, and thin in width.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] These hardness results imply that recursive halving is the fastest possible algorithm for achieving full proportionality with contiguous pieces, and it is the fastest possible deterministic algorithm for achieving even partial proportionality and even with disconnected pieces.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] The only case in which it can be improved is with randomized algorithms guaranteeing partial proportionality with disconnected pieces.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] If the players are able to cut with only finite precision, then the Ω(n log n) lower bound also includes randomized protocols.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] The proportionality criterion can be generalized to situations in which the entitlements of the partners are not equal.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] For example, the resource may belong to two shareholders such that Alice holds 8/13 and George holds 5/13.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] This leads to the criterion of *weighted proportionality* (WPR): there are several weights *wi* that sum up to 1, and every partner *i* should receive at least a fraction *wi* of the resource by their own valuation.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] Several algorithms can be used to find a WPR division.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] The main challenge is that the number of cuts may be large, even when there are only two partners.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] A *super-proportional division* is a division in which each partner receives strictly more than 1/*n* of the resource by their own subjective valuation.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] Of course such a division does not always exist: when all partners have exactly the same value functions, the best we can do is give each partner exactly 1/*n*.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] So a necessary condition for the existence of a super-proportional division is that not all partners have the same value measure.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] The surprising fact is that, when the valuations are additive and non-atomic, this condition is also sufficient.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] I.e., when there are at least *two* partners whose value function is even slightly different, then there is a super-proportional division in which *all* partners receive more than 1/*n*.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] In addition to the usual constraint that all pieces must be connected, in some cases there are additional constraints.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] In particular, when the *cake* to divide is a disputed territory lying among several countries, it may be required that the piece allocated to each country is adjacent to its current location.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] A proportional division with this property always exists and can be found by combining the Last Diminisher protocol with geometric tricks involving conformal mappings.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] When the "cake" to be divided is two-dimensional, such as a land-estate or an advertisement space in print or electronic media, it is often required that the pieces satisfy some geometric constraints, in addition to connectivity.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] For example, it may be required that each piece be a square, a fat rectangle, or generally a fat object.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] With such fatness constraints, a proportional division usually does not exist, but a partially-proportional division usually exists and can be found by efficient algorithms.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] In addition to being proportional, it is often required that the division be economically efficient, i.e., maximize the social welfare (defined as the sum of the utilities of all agents).
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] For example, consider a cake which contains 500 gram chocolate and 500 gram vanilla, divided between two partners one of whom wants only the chocolate and the other wants only the vanilla.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] Many cake-cutting protocols will give each agent 250 gram chocolate and 250 gram vanilla.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] This division is proportional because each partner receives 0.5 of his total value so the normalized social welfare is 1.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] However, this partition is very inefficient because we could give all the chocolate to one partner and all the vanilla to the other partner, achieving a normalized social welfare of 2.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] The *optimal proportional division* problem is the problem of finding a proportional allocation that maximizes the social welfare among all possible proportional allocations.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] This problem currently has a solution only for the very special case where the cake is a 1-dimensional interval and the utility density functions are linear (i.e.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] When the utility functions are not normalized (i.e. we allow each partner to have a different value for the whole cake), the problem is even NP-hard to approximate within a factor of 1/√*n*.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] Truthfulness is not a property of a division but rather a property of the protocol.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] All protocols for proportional division are *weakly truthful* in that each partner acting according to his true valuation is guaranteed to get at least 1/*n* (or 1/*an* in case of a partially proportional protocol) regardless of what the other partners do.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] Even if all other partners make a coalition with the only intent to harm him, he will still receive his guaranteed proportion.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] However, most of the protocols are not *strongly truthful* in that some partners may have an incentive to lie in order to receive even more than the guaranteed share.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] This is true even for the simple divide and choose protocol: if the cutter knows the preferences of the chooser, he can cut a piece which the chooser values as slightly less than 1/2, but which the cutter himself values as much more than 1/2.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] There are truthful mechanisms for achieving a perfect division; since a perfect division is proportional, these are also truthful mechanisms for proportional division.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] Pick a random partition (see for more details).
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] If the random partition happens to be super-proportional according to the reported value measures, then implement it.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] Otherwise, use a truthful mechanism for providing a perfect division.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] When a super-proportional division exists, there is a positive chance that it will be picked in step 2.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] Hence the expected value of every truthful partner is strictly more than 1/*n*.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] (b) If the picked partition is not super-proportional because it gives only the liar a value of 1/*n* or less, then the only effect of lying is to make the mechanism think that the partition *is* super-proportional and implement it, which only harms the liar himself.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] (c) If the picked partition is truly not super-proportional because it gives another partner a value of 1/*n* or less, then lying has no effect at all since the partition will not be implemented in any case.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] When the resource to divide is undesirable (like in chore division), a proportional division is defined as a division giving each person *at most* 1/*n* of the resource (i.e. the sign of inequality is inversed).
[src:fair-division-algorithms/proportional-cake-cutting] Most algorithms for proportional division can be adapted to chore division in a straightforward way.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] In the typical setting, there are n partners who rent together an n -room house for cost fixed by the homeowner.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Each housemate may have different preferences — one may prefer a large room, another may prefer a room with a view to the main road, etc.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] There are several properties that we would like the assignment to satisfy.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Envy-freeness implies Pareto-efficiency.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] *Proof:* Suppose by contradiction that there exists an alternative assignment, with the same price-vector, that is strictly better for at least one partner.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Then, in the current allocation, that partner is envious.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] The cardinal assumption implies the ordinal assumption, since given a valuation vector it is always possible to construct a preference relation.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] The ordinal assumption is more general and puts less mental burden on the partners.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] *No externalities*: The preference relation of each partner depends on the rooms and the rents, but not on choices made by others.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] *Miserly tenants*: every tenant weakly prefers a free room (a room with a rent of 0) over any other room.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] *Topologically closed preference sets*: A partner who prefers a room for a convergent sequence of prices, prefers that room at the limiting price.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Then each pricing scheme is a point in an $(n-1)$ -dimensional simplex with n vertices in $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] This results in a Sperner coloring of the dual simplex, and thus there exists a small sub-simplex which corresponds to an approximate envy-free assignment of rooms and rents.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Su's protocol returns a sequence of allocations which converges to an envy-free allocation.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Hence, the outcome satisfies the NN and EF requirements.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Su's Rental Harmony protocol has been popularized in several news articles, and has several online implementations.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Azriely and Shmaya generalize Su's solution to a situation in which the capacity of each room may be larger than one (i.e., several partners can live in the same room).
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] *No externalities*: All partners like free rooms.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] *Miserly partners*: The preferences are continuous in prices.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Their solution is constructive in the same sense as Su's solution - there is a procedure that approximates the solution to any given precision.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] There are several reasons such generality can be useful.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] The price-vector may give the partner some indication on the quality of rooms.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] The price-vector may allow the partner to predict, to some extent, what kind of people are going to live in the neighboring rooms.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Irrationality effects, e.g. framing effects.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] If room B and room C are of the same quality and have the same price, then the partner may buy A.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] But, if room B becomes more expensive, then the partner may switch to C, thinking that "it is the same as B but in bargain price..".
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Su suggests to weaken this assumption in the following way: each partner never chooses the most expensive room if there is a free room available.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] This does not require the person to choose the free room.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] In particular, this will hold if a person always prefers a free room to a room costing at least $1/(n-1)$ of the total rent.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] However, even this weakened assumption might be unrealistic, as in the above example.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Segal-Halevi shows that the assumption can be weakened even further.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Let us say that a price *T* is **too high** for some agent *i* if, whenever some room costs T and some other room is free, no agent prefers the room that costs *T*.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Rental harmony exists whenever there exists a price that is too high for all agents.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] This assumption is weaker than the miserly tenants assumption, and weaker than quasilinearity.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] It is an open question, whether there is an even weaker assumption that guarantees existence of rental harmony.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] As explained above, the input to the cardinal version is a matrix of bids: every partner has to submit a bid to each room, saying how much (in dollars) this room is worth for him.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] It is usually assumed that agents have quasilinear utilities, so that their utility to a room is their value for the room minus the room price.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] A key notion in the cardinal solutions is a **maxsum** (aka **utilitarian**) allocation.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] This is an allocation of partners to rooms, that maximizes the sum of bids.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] The problem of finding a maxsum allocation is known as the assignment problem, and it can be solved by the Hungarian algorithm in time $O(n^{3})$ (where n is the number of partners).
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Every EF allocation is maxsum and every maxsum allocation is PE.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] The two requirements of envy-freeness and non-negative payments are not always compatible.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Here, the only maxsum allocation is giving room 1 to partner 1 and room 2 to partner 2.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] In order to make sure partner 2 does not envy, partner 1 must pay 115 and partner 2 must pay -15.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] In this example, the sum of valuations is more than the total cost.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] If the sum of valuations equals the total cost, and there are two or three partners, then there always exists an EF and NN allocation.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Note that this example does not occur in the ordinal version, since the ordinal protocols make the "Miserly Partners" assumption - partners always prefer free rooms.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] When this assumption holds, there always exists an EF+NN allocation.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] But, in the above example, the assumption does not hold and an EF+NN allocation does not exist.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Therefore, the protocols in the cardinal version have to compromise between EF and NN.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Each protocol makes a different compromise.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] If the max-sum is less than the total cost, then the problem is unsolvable, since the partners do not want to pay the total amount required by the houseowner.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] If the max-sum exactly equals the total cost, then the rooms are allocated and the partners pay their valuations.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] If the max-sum is more than the total cost, then the prices are lowered based on the *gap* between these prices and the next-lowest valuations (see the book for more details).
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] The idea behind the last step is that the next-lowest valuations represent the "competition" on the rooms.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] If there a room is more wanted by the next-highest bidder, then it should cost more.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] This is similar in spirit to the Vickrey auction.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] However, while in the Vickrey auction the payment is entirely independent of the partner's bid, in the Gap procedure the payment is only partially independent.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Therefore, the Gap procedure is not strategyproof.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] The Gap Procedure always assigns non-negative prices.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Because the assignment is maxsum, it is obviously also Pareto-efficient.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] I.e, the Gap procedure satisfies NN and PE but not EF.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Moreover, the Gap Procedure may return non-envy-free allocations, even when EF allocations exist.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Brams relates to this problem saying that: "Gap prices do take into account the competitiveness of bidding for goods, which makes the pricing mechanism market-oriented.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Although envy-freeness is a desirable property, I prefer a marketlike mechanism when there is a conflict between these two properties; partners *should* pay more when bids are competitive, even at the sacrifice of causing envy".
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Haake, Raith and Su present the Compensation Procedure.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] There is a "qualification requirement" for a partner: the sum of his bids must be at least the total cost.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] The procedure works in the following steps.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Charge from each partner the value of the bundle allocated to him.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] If all partners satisfy the qualification requirement, then the money in the pool is sufficient, and there may be some remaining *surplus*.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Eliminate envy by compensating envious partners.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] There are at most $n-1$ rounds of compensation.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] The procedure is fully descriptive and says explicitly which compensations should be made, and in what order.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Moreover, it is simple enough to be carried out without computer support.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] The sum of compensations made in all rounds is the smallest sum that is required to eliminate envy, and it never exceeds the surplus.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] If some surplus remains, it can be divided in any way that does not create envy, e.g., by giving an equal amount to each partner (the paper discusses other options that may be considered "fairer").
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] When there are many item and complex constraints, the initial step - finding a maxsum allocation - may be difficult to calculate without a computer.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] In this case, the Compensation Procedure may start with an arbitrary allocation.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] In this case, the procedure might conclude with an allocation that contains *envy-cycles*.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] These cycles can be removed by moving bundles along the cycle.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] This strictly increases the total sum of utilities.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Hence, after a bounded number of iterations, a maxsum allocation will be found, and the procedure can continue as above to create an envy-free allocation.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] The Compensation Procedure might charge some partners a negative payment (i.e., give the partners a positive amount of money).
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] This means that the Compensation Procedure is EF (hence also PE) but not NN.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] "we do not preclude the possibility that an individual may end up being paid by the others to take a bundle of goods.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] In the context of fair division, we do not find this problematic at all.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Indeed, if a group does not wish to exclude any of its members, then there is no reason why the group should not subsidize a member for receiving an undesired bundle.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Moreover, the qualification requirement guarantees that subsidization is never a consequence of a player's insufficient valuation of the complete set of objects to be distributed".
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] "a housemate who is assigned a room with a negative room rent is subsidized by some of other housemates.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] In such a situation, some housemates may prefer to leave the room with negative room rent unused and to exclude the housemate who is assigned that room, because they may receive larger discount.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] In order to avoid such a situation, negative room rents must be avoided".
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Abdulkadiroğlu et al. suggest a market-based approach.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] It is a combination of an ascending auction and a descending auction.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Calculate the *demand-set* of each partner: the room or set of rooms he likes most at the current prices.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Calculate the set of over-demanded rooms (rooms that are demanded by more partners than the number of rooms; see the paper for exact definition).
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Simultaneously, decrease the price of all other rooms in the same rate, such that the sum of prices of all rooms always equals the total cost.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] At each instant, update the demand of each partner and the set of over-demanded rooms.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] When the set of over-demanded rooms is empty, stop and apply Hall's marriage theorem to allocate to each partner a room in their demand-set.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] In practice, it is not necessary to change the price continuously, since the only interesting prices are prices in which the demand-sets of one or more partners change.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] It is possible to calculate the set of interesting prices in advance, and convert the continuous-price auction to a discrete-price auction.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] This discrete-price auction stops after a finite number of steps.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] The returned allocation is always envy-free.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] The prices may be negative, like in the procedure of Haake et al.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] However, in contrast to that procedure, the prices are non-negative if there exists an EF allocation with non-negative prices.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Max-sum implies envy-freeness: given a price-vector *p*, if there is an allocation x with which *p* is envy-free, then *p* is envy-free for *any* maxsum allocation.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Find a minsum price-vector (a vector in which the sum of prices is minimized), subject to the envy-freeness constraint.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Such price-vector is a solution of a linear programming problem, and it can be found by the Bellman–Ford algorithm.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] If the min-sum equals the total cost, implement the maxsum allocation with the minsum prices and finish.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] If the min-sum is less than the total cost, then increase all prices in a constant rate until the sum equals the total cost (i.e., add to each price: $(cost-minsum)/n$ ).
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Changing all prices by the same amount ensures that the assignment remains envy-free.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] If the min-sum is more than the total cost, then there is no solution satisfying both NN and EF.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] The runtime complexity of both finding maxsum allocation and finding minsum prices is $O(n^{3})$ .
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Aragones presented a polytime algorithm for finding an EF solution that, among all EF solutions, maximizes the smallest payment by an agent (it is called the Money Rawlsian solution).
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Gal, Mash, Procaccia and Zick, based on their experience with the rent division application in the Spliddit website, note that envy-freeness alone is insufficient to guarantee the satisfaction of the participants.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Therefore, they build an algorithmic framework, based on linear programming, for calculating allocations that are both envy-free and optimize some criterion.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Based on theoretic and experimental tests, they conclude that the egalitarian rule - maximizing the minimum utility of an agent subject to envy-freeness - attains optimal results.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Note that, since their solution is always EF, it might return negative prices.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] The maximin solution is implemented in the spliddit.org website and in the pref.tools website.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Peters, Procaccia and Zhu study a practical setting in which agents may be unsure about their valuations.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Most papers in the cardinal model assume that agents have Quasilinear utility functions - their utility is the room value minus the price.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] But in reality, agents have budget constraints - if the room price is above their budget, the utility drops much faster than linearly.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] In fact, an agent always prefers any room with a price at most his budget, to a room with a price larger than his budget.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] In this case, there may not exist a price-vector that is both EF and affordable.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] For example, suppose the total rent is 1000, there are two rooms and two agents with identical valuations: 800 and 200, and identical budget: 600.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] There is a single price-vector in which both agents have the same quasilinear utility: (800,200); but the agent in room 1 does not have enough budget to pay.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] In contrast, there are affordable price-vectors, e.g.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Note that the condition of "price too high" still holds in this case, but the preferences are not continuous (the agents prefer only room 2 when p1>600 and only room 1 when p1<=600).
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Procaccia, Velez and Yu present an efficient algorithm for finding whether there exists an allocation that is both EF and affordable.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] If so, it finds an allocation that, among all EF affordable allocations, maximizes the smallest utility (as in egalitarian item allocation).
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Both these relaxations significantly enlarge the set of EF allocations.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] However, even with each of these relaxations, an EF allocation might not exist.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Velez studies EF rent division under *soft budget constraints*.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Each agent reports their values for rooms, their budget, and their marginal disutility from having to pay more than the budget (e.g. the interest rate).
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] He presents an algorithm that find an EF rent division that is, moreover, egalitarian (max min utility), or money-Rawlsian (min-max rent), or satisfies one of other similar conditions.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] The run-time is in O(*nk*+*c*), where n is the number of agents, *k* is the number of different disutility values (e.g. different interest rates), and *c*>2 is some constant.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Velez studies the strategic properties of these algorithms.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] He shows that, the complete-information non-cooperative outcomes of each of the algorithms are exactly the EF allocations w.r.t. true preferences, iff the number of allowed disutilities is bounded.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Arunachaleswaran, Barman and Rathi study a setting substantially more general than quasilinear, in which the utility of each agent from each room can be any piecewise linear function of the rent.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] This setting generalizes the soft budget constraint.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] As there is a too-high price, an EF allocation always exists.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] They show an FPTAS - an algorithm that finds an allocation that is EF up to (1+*ε*), in time polynomial in 1/*ε* and *nk*+*c*, where n is the number of agents, *k* is the number of different disutility values (e.g. different interest rates), and *c*>2 is some constant.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] They also show that the problem lines in the intersection of the complexity classes PPAD and PLS.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] All protocols surveyed so far assume that the partners reveal their true valuations.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] They are not strategyproof - a partner can gain by reporting false valuations.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Indeed, **strategyproofness is incompatible with envy-freeness**: there is no deterministic strategyproof protocol that always returns an envy-free allocation.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] This is true even when there are only two partners and when the prices are allowed to be negative.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] The only maxsum allocation is giving room 1 to partner 1 and room 2 to partner 2.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Let $p_{2}$ be the price of room 2 (so that the price of room 1 is $100-p_{2}$ ).
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] To ensure partner 1 does not envy, we must have $p_{2}\geq x/2$ .
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] To ensure partner 2 does not envy, we must have $p_{2}\leq y/2$ .
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Suppose a deterministic protocol sets the price $p_{2}$ to some value in $[x/2,y/2]$ .
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] If the price is more than $x/2$ , then partner 2 has an incentive to report a lower value of y , which is still above x , in order to push his payment down towards $x/2$ .
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Similarly, if the price is less than $y/2$ , then partner 1 has an incentive to report a higher value of x , which is still below y , in order to push the payment of partner 2 up towards $y/2$ (and thus push his own payment down).
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Hence, the mechanism cannot be strategyproof.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Researchers have coped with this impossibility in two ways.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] There is a variant of the problem in which, instead of assuming that the total house cost is fixed, we assume that there is a maximum cost for each room.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] In this variant, a strategyproof mechanism exists: the deterministic allocation-rule selecting the min-sum cost is strategyproof.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] This result can be generalized for greater flexibility on the indivisible objects, and a proof of coalitional strategy-proofness.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Going back to the original rental-harmony problem, it is possible to consider **randomized mechanisms**.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] A randomized mechanism returns a probability distribution over room-assignments and rent-divisions.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] A randomized mechanism is *truthful in expectation* if no partner can increase the expected value of his utility by mis-reporting his valuations to the rooms.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] **Guaranteed Probability of Envy-Freeness (GPEF)** means that there is a certain probability p such that, regardless of the partners' valuations, with probability at least p , the outcome will be envy-free.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] It is possible to achieve a GPEF of $1/n$ in the following way: find an envy-free assignment; choose an integer $i\in \{0,\dots ,n-1\}$ at random; and move each partner cyclically i rooms to the right.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] This randomized mechanism is truthful-in-expectation, since every partner has an equal probability to land in each room and the expected payment is $1/n$ of the total cost, regardless of the partner's bid.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] The probability of having an EF allocation is the probability that $i=0$ , which is exactly $1/n$ .
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] This is not encouraging, since the probability of envy-freeness converges to 0 when the number of partners grows.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] But it is impossible to do better: in every truthful-in-expectation mechanism, the GPEF is at most $1/n$ .
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] **Expected Number of Envy-Free partners (ENEF)** means that there is a certain integer N such that, if we average the number of partners who do not envy in all possible outcomes of the mechanism, then regardless of the partners' valuations, the expectation is at least N .
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] The ENEF criterion seems more appropriate than the GPEF criterion, because it measures not only the probability of entire envy-freeness, but also the quality of the cases in which the allocation is not entirely envy-free.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] The maximum ENEF of a truthful-in-expectation mechanism is at most $n-1+1/n$ .
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] It is possible to attain this bound for $n=2$ .
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] For $n>2$ , there is a truthful-in-expectation mechanism that almost attains this bound: the ENEF is $n-1$ .
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Use the VCG mechanism to calculate a maxsum assignment and payments.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Combine the outcomes in a way which guarantees that the total payment equals the total cost (see the paper for details).
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] It is possible to show that: (a) the mechanism is truthful-in-expectation; (b) all partners except the ignored partner do not envy.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Simulations show that in about 80% of the cases, the GPEF of this mechanism is also at its maximum of $1/n$ .
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] A possible relaxation of the strategyproofness requirement is to try to minimize the "degree of manipulability".
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] This is defined by counting, for each profile, the number of agents who can manipulate the rule.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Maximally-preferred fair allocation rules are the minimally (individually and coalitionally) manipulable fair and budget-balanced allocation rules according to this new concept.
[src:fair-division-algorithms/rental-harmony] Such rules choose allocations with the maximal number of agents for whom the utility is maximized among all fair and budget-balanced allocations.
